Go to the directory:
/home/thanni/Documents/git-workspace/StudentWebApp/StudentManifest

Run the below commend run the yml file
kubectl apply -f studentwebappdeployment.yml

Run the commadns:
kubectl get pods -o wide
kubectl get svc
kubectl get rs
kubectl delete all --all
kubectl get deployment
kubectl scale deployment javastudwebapp --replicas 5

kubectl  get pods –o all

Deployment internally used by the ReplicySet.
Delete Deployment:
Kubectl delete deployment <<deployment_name>>
Kubectl delete deployment studentdemodeployment  If you delete the deployment all pods are deleed.

kubectl delete deployment studentdemodeployment

1. List all Pods
    kubectl get pods
    Add -o wide to see Node/IP info:
    kubectl get pods -o wide

2. Check Pod details
    kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
    This shows events, container state, restarts, readiness, failures.

3. Check Pod logs
    For your Spring Boot app container:
    kubectl logs <pod-name>
    If multiple containers inside the pod:
    kubectl logs <pod-name> -c studentwebappcontainer
    Follow logs like tail -f:
    kubectl logs -f <pod-name>

4. Exec inside the pod
    Useful to test connectivity or debug:
    kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- /bin/bash
    or if alpine-based:
    kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- sh

5. Test application from inside the cluster
    A — Using kubectl port-forward (most convenient)
        kubectl port-forward service/studentwebappsvc 8080:80
        Now you can access your service locally:
        http://localhost:8080
    B — Using Service NodePort (Minikube)
        Check service:
        kubectl get svc studentwebappsvc
        Then get Minikube IP:
        minikube ip
        Example access:
        http://<minikube-ip>:30785

6. Test if Pod is responding internally
    Inside the pod:
    kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- curl http://localhost:8080

7. Check Pod events (crashes, restarts)
    kubectl get pods
    kubectl describe pod <pod-name> | grep -i 'error\|fail\|crash'

8. Common things to verify for Spring Boot app
    Pod is in Running state
    kubectl get pods

    Container logs show app has started
    kubectl logs <pod>

    Service is created
    kubectl get svc

    Port-forward test works
    kubectl port-forward svc/studentwebappsvc 8080:80

    Minikube NodePort test works
    http://<minikube-ip>:30785

kubectl get pods -o wide
kubectl get svc

